<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-04-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="60" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d60">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00 R 29/711</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Belgian Ambassador</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">De Cartier</hi></persName>)<note n="42" xml:id="d60fn42">The
                                same, <hi rend="italic">mutatis mutandis</hi>, to the British,
                                Italian, and Japanese Ambassadors.</note></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-04-29"><hi rend="italic">April 29,
                                1921</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: I have received today
                            the enclosed memorandum from Berlin<note n="43" xml:id="d60fn43">See
                                telegram no. 464, Apr. 28, from the Commissioner at Berlin, <ref target="#pg_53">p. 53</ref>.</note> correcting the memorandum of
                            April 24th, with respect to reparations, in the particulars noted.</p>
                        <p>Believe me [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E.
                            Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>